44.title: Jock Itch
dlg: Know that, just like ringworm of the skin, it may be contagious and it can sometimes accompany athlete's foot and ringworm.

0.header:
This is a result of a fungus Tinea Cruris growing in the groin area.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend to help with the jock itch you may be experiencing.

1.header:
Alright.
Start by making sure you are looking at jock itch.

There are other conditions that can cause itching in the groin area such as eczema, crabs, chemical irritation, drug reactions, psoriasis and so on.

2.header:
Do you have itching in the groin?

Or skin folds of the inner thighs?

3.header:
No?
You may not be looking at jock itch then.

If you still think it is jock itch let's continue and see what we can come up with.

4.header:
What about itching in the anal area?

And / or buttocks?

6.header:
Does the area have patches that are red, scaly?

Raised?

7.header:
Yes?
Possibly jock itch, but then again it could be eczema. So let's continue.

8.header:
Are there patches that are flaking, ringed?

And / or blistering?

9.header:
Yes?
Thinking jock itch, but could be eczema. Let's continue.

10.header: Is the area unusually darker or lighter than your regular skin color?

11.header:
Yes?
Jock itch may cause this. This is one of the symptoms.

12.header: Are the penis and testicles inflammed and itchy also?

13.header:
Yes?
Hmmm. You may not be looking at jock itch.

Jock itch usually stays around the creases in the upper thigh and does not involve the testicles or penis.

If your scrotum is inflammed, you may be looking at something like candidal intertrigo or lichen simplex chronicus.

You will have to see a doctor for this.

14.header: Have you tried something for more than 2 weeks and no improvement?

15.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Time to seek further evaluation.
  • May be looking at a mixed infection.

Like to visit the nearest urgent care or Continue?

16.header: Is the affected area swollen or draining?

17.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at a mixed infection.
  • Over the counter medications won't cut this.

18.header:
If still thinking jock itch, let's see what a pharmacist recommend.

Would you like to see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter for jock itch or think you should seek urgent care from the discusssions so far?

45.title: Hemorrhoids
dlg:
The pressure can be due to:

  • Constipation
  • Straining during bowel movements
  • Pregnancy
  • Childbirth
  • Sitting for long periods of time
  • Other causes.

0.header:
Increased pressure in the veins of the anal area can cause this.

This pressure cause the veins to swell leading to hemorrhoids.


Let's see how we can help with this. You will answer a few questions first.

1.header:
Is there bright red blood in the stool?

Toilet bowl or tissue?

2.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • The American Gastroenterological Association position on this is that all patients who report rectal bleeding should undergo sigmoidoscopy.
  • Rectal bleeding is not specific to hemorrhoid, so the doctor will have to rule out other things that might cause bleeding such as anal fissure, fistula, abscess, or even colorectal cancer.

Call 911 if you are ...

  1. Bleeding and
  2. feel dizzy
  3. Lightheaded or
  4. faint.

If you've had hemorrhoid before and would like to continue, then let's move forward.

3.header:
Is this hemorrhoid Internal?
(just inside the anus)
OR  External?
(at the opening of the anus and may be hanging outside)

10.header:
This is usually symptomless unless the swollen vein gets blocked by a blood clot.

When this happen, you will feel severe pain. Let's see if this is the situation you are looking at.

11.header: Is the hemorrhoid tender?

13.header: Is it very painful?

14.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need professional evaluation to rule out blood clot.

15.header: Is the hemorrhoid purplishly swollen?

16.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible infection
  • Possible blood clot

17.header:
Hemorrhoids that is external and very painful require urgent care.

Most likely, the swollen vein is blocked by a blood clot.

The doctor may have to do an excision of the hemorrhoid to relieve pain after numbing the area with something like lidocaine.

If the hemorrhoid is not painful but just an inconvenience, let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter to help shrink it.

20.header:
Let's make sure you are looking at hemorrhoids.
Do you feel pain during bowel movements?

22.header:
What about while sitting down?
Do you feel anal pain?

23.header: Are you experiencing itching in the anal area?

24.header: Do you feel one or more hard lumps in the rectal area?

25.header:
Yes?
Most likely looking at hemorrhoids

Internal hemorrhoids sometimes cause mucus discharge and a sensation of incomplete evacuation.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter to help with this situation.

26.header:
No?
Well, with hemorrhoid, you will feel a hard lump in the rectal area.

If you are not sure it is hemorrhoids, visit a nearby urgent care clinic for further evaluation.

If you are thinking hemorrhoids, let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter for relief.

0.header:
Pinworms usually show no symptoms until there is intense itching.

Let's see what we can come up with.
But first, how do you know you are looking at pinworm infestation anyway?

Let's start with that.

1.header: Are you having serious itching in the anal region?

2.header:
No?
You may not have pinworms then.

This is the most common symptom of a pinworm infestation.

The females migrate at night to the outside of the anus and lay eggs.

The sticky, gelatinous substance in which the eggs are deposited and the crawling of the female worm around the anal region cause the itching especially at night.

If there is any kind of itching in the anal area, let's continue

3.header: What about difficulty sleeping due to itching at night?

5.header: Is the area around the anus irritated and sore as a result of constant scratching?

7.header:
If you are a female, irritation of the vagina may occur if an adult worm enters the vagina.

Is this the case with you?

9.header:
Have you lost appetite to eat?

Or some weight lately?

This is not too common but can occur in cases with severe infection.

11.header:
Diagnosis of pinworm infestation can be done in one of two ways listed below.

1. Finding the thread-like female worms in the anal area especially at night or in the morning (female worms are about 10 mm or ½ inch long while males average 3 mm).
   See if you can get someone to use a magnifying glass to help check you out first thing in the morning or about 2 hours after you have fallen asleep.

Or 2. Tape test:
A piece of cellophane tape is patted against the anal region first thing in the morning before bathing or using the toilet (bathing and wiping may remove eggs). This is placed, sticky side down, on a glass slide and view for eggs using a microscope.
   You may have to do this on 3 consecutive mornings. You will take them to the doctor for viewing under the microscope.

So do you think you have pinworm?

12.header:
Yes?
Alright, let's see what a pharmacist recommend to take care of the pinworm.

Remember, you may have to treat the whole family.

If you are not too sure, let's continue

13.header:
Not sure?
Give the doctor a call if you suspect pinworm infestation.

Suspect pinworm if:

  • You have intense itching in the anal region especially at night or early in the morning.
  • A family member has pinworm.
  • Difficulty sleeping due to the itching that occurs during the night.
  • Soreness of the anal region especially in the morning. You may be scratching the area at night and not know it.

Would you like to see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter to help with pinworm infestation or see the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

47.title: Menstrual Pain
dlg:
Secondary dysmenorrhea is menstrual pain that develops later in women who have had normal periods and may be related to problems in the uterus or other pelvic organs like:

  • Fibroids
  • Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID)
  • Endometriosis
  • Sexually transmitted disease
  • Intrauterine device (IUD) made of copper
  • Stress and anxiety

Your gynecologist will rule out anything that may be damaging to your health.

0.header:
This is usually occur just before and during the menstrual periods.

Let's see what you are looking at and how you can get relief using over-the-counter medications.

1.header: Is this cramping pain in the lower abdomen?

3.header:
Is this like a sharp pain that comes and goes?

An aching pain that comes and goes?

5.header:
Does this pain sometimes radiate to your lower back?

Or thighs?

7.header: Are you experiencing nausea and/or vomiting with this menstrual pain?

9.header: What about feeling dizzy?

11.header:
Are you sweating with this menstrual pain?

Or having diarrhea?

13.header:
There are two types of period pain:
primary and secondary.
  1. Primary
    Due to your menstrual period alone.
  2. Secondary
    Due to a medical condition such as ovarian cysts (fluid-filled sacs), endometriosis or even using IUDs.

With this in mind, let's see the best course of action to tackle this problem.

A few questions to rule out serious urgent care situations.
